<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-443-053  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 443 053.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  Oct 1990 v3 n11 p28(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>dBASE IV 1.1 checks in; a group of industry luminaries debate thestate of the Dbase market now that Ashton-Tate has dropped theother shoe. (panel discussion)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Strehlo, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A group of leaders in the dBASE community discusses broad issuessurrounding the release of Ashton Tate Corp's dBASE IV 1.1.andP;  ThedBASE industry needs a core standard to make it easier to go fromone version of dBASE to another and to avoid confusion in the wakeof the many new operating systems to which dBASE is being ported.andO;Ashton-Tate should take leadership in establishing a standardsorganization.andP;  There is a perception that the stability of thedBASE market depends on the health of Ashton-Tate.andP;  If Ashton-Tatedeclines, vendors such as Fox Software may not be strong enough totake the company's place There is disagreement as to whetherAshton-Tate owns the dBASE market at this time but it is clearthat if it does not take a leadership position, the market willcontinue to be segmented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashton-Tate Corp. (products).andO;Product:   dBASE IV 1.1 (Data base management system) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsIndustry AnalysisEvaluationOutlookDominationCompetitionStandardizationCompatible SoftwareLikelihood of Survival.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Adams, Pat (attitudes); Rettig, Tom (attitudes); Freeland, Russell(attitudes); Irwin, Michael (attitudes); Powell, Jordan(attitudes); Hakim, Jack (attitudes); Schnapp, Marc (attitudes);Lima, Tony (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>